{{refimprove|date=May 2018}}
The '''HAF601''' is a regulation in the [[People's Republic of China]] dealing with the manufacture of safety class equipment for the [[Nuclear power in China|Chinese nuclear power]] market. All domestic Chinese firms manufacturing mechanical equipment of Safety Class 1, 2, or 3, or electrical equipment of safety Class 1E, must obtain HAF601 registration before supplying such equipment to a Chinese nuclear power plant<ref>http://2016.export.gov/china/build/groups/public/@eg_cn/documents/webcontent/eg_cn_067072.pdf</ref>. This regulation also applies to international (i.e. non-Chinese) firms producing equipment from a factory within China. For equipment manufactured outside of China and imported into the country, a [[HAF 604]] certificate is required instead. HAF stands for "he anquan fagui" (核安全法) and means "nuclear safety laws" in Chinese<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nicobargroup.com/certification-advisory-haf604-en/|title=HAF604 Certification Information - Imported Nuclear Safety Equipment|author=|date=|website=Nicobar Group}}</ref>. The HAF system has been applied in the China nuclear industry since 2007 and has gradually replaced use of the [[ASME]] Stamp system.
The HAF601 is governed and administered by the Chinese nuclear safety regulatory authority, the [[National Nuclear Safety Administration]] (NNSA). This should not be confused with the United States' [[National Nuclear Security Administration]] which shares the same acronym.
